'''Robert Trumble''' (1920<U+2014> ) is an [[Australia]]n musician and author. Son of international [[cricket]]er [[Hugh Trumble]],  Robert dedicated his first book, ''The Golden Age of Cricket'', to his father.<ref name="Robert">{{cite news | first = Anne | last = Thompson| title = A past master | url = http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/03/14/1079199093391.html?from=storyrhs | work = [[The Age]] | date = 2004-03-15|accessdate = 2008-04-10}}</ref> It was published in [[Melbourne]] in 1968.<ref>[http://www.redrosebooks.co.uk/bookdetail.asp?id=3604 ''The Golden Age of Cricket''] at RedRoseBooks, retrieved [[May 6]] [[2008]]</ref> Robert Trumble's musical career was also noted by the Australian media. In 2003 he was awarded the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres|Chevalier dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]] for reviving the work of [[Vincent d'Indy]]. He had previously spent thirty years as a concert manager for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]. He was also commissioned to write for the [[British Music Society]] in 2004, and also published a biography of d'Indy, ''Vincent d'Indy - His Greatness and His Integrity'' in 1994 and ''The Compositions of Vincent d'Indy'' in 2000.<ref name="Robert"/>

